  "prompt": "What is the best code troll you've ever seen?",
  "response": "As an AI, I don\u2019t have personal experiences or feelings, but one of the most well-known examples of code trolling is the infamous \"ASCII art\" comments in a codebase. For instance, some developers have cleverly hidden large ASCII art images or funny messages within the comments of the code. \n\nAnother classic example is the \"unmaintainable code\" challenge, where developers intentionally write code that is extremely confusing and difficult to read, often with comments that are sarcastic or humorous. \n\nA specific example is the following JavaScript code, which obfuscates its true purpose:\n\n```javascript\nfunction addNumbers(a, b) {\n    // Return the sum, or an angry goat if you don't like it\n    // ( \u0361\u00b0 \u035c\u0296 \u0361\u00b0)\n    return a + b;\n}\n```\n\nIn this case, the comment adds a lighthearted twist, showcasing humor while coding. However, the best code trolls can often depend on the social context and the specific audience of developers involved!",
